Narrative.NarrativeTxt: I responded to 201 Newman on a burglary not in progress. Made contact with the victim who stated that someone came in her house while she was gone and stole her pocket knife and daughter's tablet.

On 1/1/19, I responded to 201 Newman St on a report of a burglary not in progress. Upon my arrival, I made contact with the home owner, Dorie Crutchfield. Ms. Crutchfield stated that while she was gone, someone got inside her house and stole her pocket knife and her daughter's tablet. Ms. Crutchfield stated that she came back to her house around 10 p.m. on 12/31/18 and changed clothes. Ms. Crutchfield stated that everything was fine when she left. Ms. Crutchfield stated that she returned to her home around 2 a.m. on 1/1/19, and that was when she noticed the items missing. Ms. Crutchfield stated that she could see wet footprints going through her home, back to her bedroom were the pocket knife was at. Ms. Crutchfield stated that it appeared that the drawers on her night stand beside her bed had been rummaged through. Ms. Crutchfield stated that she did not think anything was missing from them. Ms. Crutchfield had already moved everything around prior to my arrival. Ms. Crutchfield stated that her daughter's RCA tablet was laying on table in the living room when she left earlier, but it was now gone. Ms. Crutchfield provided the serial number to the tablet and I entered the tablet into LINK/NCIC. At this time there are no suspects in this case. There appeared to be no force of entry to any of the doors or windows.

After speaking with Jessie, I then contacted dispatch in reference to Matthew Redford and they advised he has two active warrants for his arrest. Narrative.NarrativeTxt: ON 01-03-2019, at approximately 1809, I responded to a report of a shoplifting at Walmart, 2345 Happy Valley Road.

ON 01-03-2019, at approximately 1809, I responded to a report of a shoplifting at Walmart, 2345 Happy Valley Road.
Upon arrival, I made contact with Walmart Asset Protection Officer, Sarah Moore, who advised that at approximately 1733, this date, she observed an unknown white male checking out at the "self scan" check out. Sarah stated that she observed the white male, later identified as Jason Thurman, scanning some items and then not scanning other items that he had selected. Sarah stated that she continued to observe Jason "miss scanning" items and then concealing these items along with the other items that he had scanned. Sarah stated that once Jason was complete with his transaction, he then passed all points of sale with the unscanned and concealed items without providing payment. Sarah stated that she then made contact with Jason and recovered the concealed items. I then made contact with Jason who was read his Miranda Warning that he acknowledged and agreed to speak with me further. Jason stated that the miss scanned items were unintentional and that he had legitimate hearing lose attributed to loud music. Jason stated and dispatch confirmed that he had no prior history of shoplifting. Sarah stated that Jason was apologetic and cooperative. Sarah provided a Walmart Asset Protection Report of the incident with receipt and photo of the concealed merchandise. I observed that Jason had purchased approximately $50 to $60 of the merchandise and that he had concealed approximately $55.31 of the merchandise. Sarah stated that she would be providing a copy of the surveillance video of the incident at a later date.
I obtained information for the report. Jason was cited and given a court date to appear. I then cleared the scene without further incident.

On 1/4/2019 I conducted a traffic stop on a vehicle in the parking lot of White Castle for failure to illuminate head lamps. Margaret Russell-Spaethe was sitting in the rear passenger seat of the vehicle. After running her social security number (609-52-0299) with dispatch, it was determined that she had an active warrant for her arrest. Russell-Spaethe was then detained and prior to putting her in the back of my vehicle she advised that she had a glass pipe inside of her jacket pocket. After Russell-Spaethe was placed in the back of my car, the operator of the vehicle provided me consent to search the vehicle. Officer Wesley Hicks arrived on scene to assist. I then read Russell-Spaethe her miranda warning in which she agreed to speak with me. Russell-Spaethe stated that the pipe was hers and she used it three (3) days ago to smoke methamphetamine out of. She further advised that the two (2) marijuana pipes found inside of her purse were hers as well.
The operator of the vehicle identified as Christen Branstetter was issued a citation for the following: Failure to illuminate head lamps and failure to produce insurance card (citation #DB79151).
Another passenger identified as Bruce Doll was issued a citation for Possession of Drug Paraphernalia (citation #DB79152).

On 01/06/2019 while on patrol I observed the above traveling at a high rate of speed. Radar detected subject traveling 97mph in a 70mph zone. Radar check ok. Upon traffic stop I spoke with driver Alek Branstetter. Branstetter had a very strong odor of alcohol coming from his person. Branstetter also had very slurred speech and glassy eyes. When asked if he had drank anything Branstetter stated that he had 3 or 4 alcoholic beverages. I then asked Branstetter to step out of the vehicle to perform field sobriety tests. Branstetter consented to the tests.
The first test given was the Horizontal Gaze Nystagmus (HGN) test. Branstetter showed distinct and sustained nystagmus on the test for lack of smooth pursuit, both the left and right eye showed clues. On maximum deviation Branstetter clued on both the right and left eyes as well. Branstetter also showed distinct and sustained nystagmus clues on both the left and right eye on the test of onset of nystagmus prior to 45 degrees. Branstetter also showed indicators for the vertical nystagmus. The second test Branstetter performed was the walk and turn field sobriety test. During the test Branstetter took 9 steps down and then took 11 steps back, taking 2 extra steps. Branstetter also missed touching heel to toe during the test. Branstetter also stepped off the line during the test. During the course of the test Branstetter also raised his arms for balance on several occasions. Also, at the turn Branstetter turned improperly. The next test Branstetter performed was the one leg stand. During this test Branstetter also used his arms for balance during the test. Branstetter also swayed throughout the test. Branstetter also hopped for balance and miscounted during the test. Branstetter then performed the preliminary breath test at which point he indicated the presence of alcohol on his breath. Branstetter was then taken into custody and transported to Barren County Detention Center.
Branstetter was then read the implied consent warning. Branstetter refused to speak to an attorney at that time. Branstetter then consented to a test of his breath on the intoxilizer 5000. After the 20 minute wait period Branstetter performed the intoxilizer breath test. Branstetter blew a .145 BAC on the test. Branstetter then refused to have a test taken of his blood at his own expense. Branstetter was then lodged in the Barren County Detention Center. ACDLC.

On 01/06/2019, I responded to 800 Cleveland Avenue apartment B12 in reference to a physical altercation. Upon arrival Sgt.Houchens and myself made contact with Bonnie Gomez, the attendant at B12. Gomez advised she was inside the residence when she heard a loud banging at her front door. Gomez stated upon opening the door, her daughter Alexis Schooley and her boyfriend, Trenton Powell were standing there. Powell advised that they wanted the rest of their property out of the residence, as they have been staying there along with a cellphone that was allegedly Alexis Schooleys. Gomez advised Powell that he could not come into the residence and retrieve the items but her daughter, Alexis Schooley could. Gomez advised that Powell then became aggressive, grabbing her wrist and attempted to pull Gomez outside of the residence. Gomez advised that once Powell grabbed her, Powell stretched his arm back in a position in attempt to make it look like he was going punch her. Gomez sustained a minor cut from the altercation as she stated she must of cut it trying to hold on to the door while she was getting pulled from her residence. Barren Metcalfe EMS responded to the scene and treated Gomez for her cut.
While the altercation was taking place, Gomez's son grabbed an air soft pistol and fired one round striking Powell in the neck. After being struck Gomez stated that Powell and Schooley returned to their ca which was parked in front of the residence. Gomez stated she came back inside of her residence and called the police.
Powell advised he didn't wish to press charges as Gomez decided she would press charges over the Incident. Gomez was referred to the County Attorney.

Narrative.NarrativeTxt: On 01/04/2018 I responded to the Holiday Inn Express at 208 Wall St. in reference to a drug complaint. Upon arrival officers made contact with Toriano Huffman. Huffman was ultimately charged with possession of marijuana and issued a citation. On 01/04/2018 I responded to the Holiday Inn Express at 208 Wall St. in reference to a drug complaint. Upon arrival officers made contact with Toriano Huffman. Huffman was ultimately charged with possession of marijuana and issued a citation. While investigating, Huffman advised that he was missing $700.00 which was located in his pants pocket in his room, 203. Huffman advised he had left the room without realizing he had left the money. Huffman advised he left the room at around 10:00 AM and returned at around 11:30 AM. Officers spoke with hotel staff and requested to view security video of the hallway outside the room. Staff advised they could not show access the video at that time but would provide the video at a later date.
Huffman advised his son had access to the room. Huffman then stated that after reviewing the video, if his son was the only other party that entered the room, he did not wish to pursue charges. On 01/08/2019 I received the video from Holiday Inn Express. Upon review of the video, It appears that after Huffman leaves the room at 10:05 AM only one person entered the room before Huffman returned at 10:47 AM. The party entering the room was identified as Carlos Sexton III, a hotel employee. Sexton enters the room at 10:24 AM and remains in the room for 3 minutes. Sexton then returned to the room at approximately 10:28 AM and entered for another 6 seconds. A short time later Sexton returns to the room yet again, along with housekeeping staff, but no one enters the room. A short time later, Huffman enters the room before exiting a short time later, rushing down the stairs.
Holiday Inn Express employees advised that Sexton's employment has been terminated. Holiday Inn Express General Manager, Russell Yonker, provided a detailed camera footage summary, along with Sexton's information and a thumb drive containing the video. The thumb drive was logged into evidence at the Glasgow Police Department and the paperwork provided has been attached to this report.
On 01/12/2019 Sexton met with officers at the Glasgow Police Department in reference to the missing money. Sexton advised he saw one of the tenants of room 203 on the elevator that morning at around 10:30 AM. Sexton advised the tenant stated that he was done in room 203. At this time, Sexton advised, he went to room 203 to prepare the room for housekeeping to clean, which was his job as a stripper. Sexton advised that when he got to the door he smelled the odor of marijuana and entered the room. Sexton stated that he observed that there were still items in the room, so he did not leave the hallway portion of the room. When asked how long he was in the room he stated that it was 2 or 3 minutes. Sexton advised he looked for other evidence of drug activity in the room, and when he saw nothing, he remained in the room longer because he likes the smell of marijuana. Sexton then advised he left the room but returned to the room a short time later to obtain a key that he had previously dropped just inside the door. Sexton advised he then notified a supervisor that marijuana was smoked in the room. Sexton then stated that he returned a third time to the room with his supervisor to confirm the smell of marijuana. Sexton stated that he did not return to the room after that until he went with the manager when the tenant was back in the room.
The over all time line Sexton advised was accurate but the fact remains that Sexton was in the room, alone for three minutes for which time Sexton advised he was looking for evidence of drug use and "enjoying" the smell of the marijuana. Sexton provided a written statement and was released at this time.
Case closed on 01/12/2019, sent to Grand Jury.

On 01/08/2019 at approximately 12:42 PM I responded to the Dollar General on Shane Drive in reference to a female who was allegedly passed out in her vehicle. Upon arrival I observed the vehicle matching the description of the vehicle in question, attempting to pull out of the parking lot. I then made contact with the operator, Kimberly Pashley, who pulled back into her parking place upon my request. Pashley advised she was tired from working night shift but was not asleep in her vehicle. Pashley advised she was looking for an ear ring. Pashley had slurred speech and her eyes were watery. Pashley was asked to get out of the vehicle and preform Standard Field Sobriety Tests. As Pashley got out of the vehicle it became evident that she was unsteady on her feet.
Pashley showed 6 clues of impairment on the Horizontal Gaze Nystagmus Test. Pashley also failed to step heel to toe on every step of the walk and turn test. Pashley also showed a clue of impairment on the balance test. At this time Pashley was placed under arrest for Operating a Motor Vehicle Under the Influence of Alcohol, Drugs, Etc. While on scene, a search incident to arrest of the vehicle yielded a syringe with a small amount of residue of suspected Methamphetamine, located in a jacket pocket in the passenger seat. Pashley advised that she used the syringe last night and stated the liquid residue inside was Methamphetamine. Also located in the vehicle was a package Kratum. Pashley was then transported to TJ Samson Hospital where she consented to a test of her blood after being read implied consent. After the test was conducted Pashley was transported to the Barren County Detention Center without incident.

On Wednesday January 9th, 2019 Officer Hicks, Officer Burgan, and I responded to 400 West Front Street in reference to a drug complaint called in by a female choosing to remain anonymous. The caller advised that Wesley Pitcock was at 400 West Front Street using Methamphetamine. Caller advised Pitcock sent her a picture at the residence on West Front Street stating that he was using Methamphetamine because "he lost the love of his life". Officers knocked on the door, and Amber Morgan and James Jaggers came to the door. Officer Hicks asked Morgan and Jaggers if Pitcock was inside, and they stated "no". Officer Hicks asked permission for officers to come inside and do a sweep of the residence for Pitcock. Officer Hicks was also advised that Christopher Jesse may possibly be at the residence, and Jesse has three active warrants for his arrest. Jaggers and Morgan allowed officers inside without incident. While looking for other people inside the residence, Officer Hicks observed several plastic baggies on a bed in the residence and a white pill that was broke in half. The numbers "04" were inscribed on the pill, and the pill was suspected to be Hydrocodone (Schedule 2 narcotic). Officer Hicks read Jaggers and Morgan their Miranda Rights, and both agreed to speak with officers. Jaggers stated that the pill belonged to his sister, Brittney Jaggers, who was not at the residence. Jaggers and Morgan stated that Brittney left the residence prior to our arrival. Narrative.NarrativeTxt: Unknown male entered Dollar General, displayed weapon and demended money from the victim.

On 01-11-2019 I responded to a report of a robbery at the Dollar General at 309 W Main St. When we arrived the manager was in the back room, there were customers shopping still. OFC Rees and I went to the back room and briefly viewed the video. Manager Williams walked back to the front register. On the video we could see the W/M wearing dark blue or black jacket with gray lining, blue or black pants, white tennis shoes, and a blue Tennessee Titans knit cap. He came in the store and walked around like he was shopping. At one point he walked into the back room looking around. Eventually the male went to the counter where we could see him lean on the counter placing his left hand palm down on the counter, with his right hand he pulled a black semi-automatic handgun from inside his jacket and pointed it at Williams. Williams said that she was working when he approached the counter carrying a 6pk of Bud Ice beer. The male placed the item on the counter and presented his identification. According to Williams she turned to ring up the sale and bag the beer so she did not look at the ID. When she turned back towards the customer the male was pointing a black semi-automatic handgun at her. The male said "give me the money" Williams said she avoided looking at him in fear that he may hurt her if she did. She put the money on the counter and the male gathered it up. She said that he did not seem to be rushing at all. She asked him if he wanted the change and he responded "no". He grabbed his bag containing the beer and walked out the front door. She did not see which direction but did say that he must have gone west since she did not see him walk the other way. Williams continued to serve customers checking out at least two more while on the phone with dispatch. I asked her if he had an accent or anything, she said he had a raspy voice. When I asked her if there was any odor she said that he had a slight odor of alcohol and that he appeared to have weathered skin like he had been working outside. Lt Cowan and the other units checked the area. CSI arrived at 1701hrs and processed the scene. All units cleared at approximately 1816hrs turning the store back over to Williams.
On 01-11-2019 at approximately 1900hrs we were notified that dispatch had received information that the suspect in the Dollar General robbery was wanting to turn himself in. Barren County Sheriff's Office units went to an address at 871 Poplar School Rd Glasgow, KY. There they made contact with a male matching the description of the suspect in the robbery. The suspect was wearing the same clothing as we saw in the video. They were also able to recover a black semi-automatic handgun matching the one used in the robbery. The male was identified as Keith Byrd. Byrd was transported to the Glasgow Police Department for questioning. Byrd was read his Miranda Warnings and decided that he would not talk without a lawyer being present. The interview was terminated and Byrd was charged and transported to the Barren County Detention Center.

Saturday, January 12, 2019 at approximately 20:06 hours I observed a red passenger car traveling on West Main Street without any headlights or tail lights illuminated. I conducted a traffic stop on the vehicle and made contact with the driver identified as Jeremy White. While speaking with White I detected a strong odor of an alcoholic beverage coming from his person. I asked if he had been drinking any alcoholic beverages and White stated that he had drank two beers approximately 3 hours prior to driving. White then that they were Bud Light tall boys.
White was asked to submit to standard field sobriety. White refused to perform the walk and turn and one leg stand due to medical reasons. White stated he did not have any medical problems to prevent him from taking a HGN test. White stated he understood the directions and I conducted HGN. White showed in both eyes lack of smooth pursuit, nystagmus at maximum deviation in both eyes, and nystagmus prior to 45 degrees in both eyes. I then conducted lack of convergence and White showed lack of convergence in both eyes. White was asked to perform Modified Romberg test and White stated he understood the directions. During the test, White estimated 44 seconds in the allotted 30 seconds, White had body tremors and swayed while estimating his 30 seconds. A PBT was performed at 20:24 hours and it read .210 and at that time
White was arrested and transported to TJ Samson Hospital. Implied consent was read and White refused to contact an attorney. White then consented to a blood test and White refused a blood test of his own.
White was then transported to Barren County Jail and during a more thorough search I located in a jacket pocket inside of the jacket that White was wearing an orange pill bottle with a green leafy substance suspected to be Marijuana inside of it. White stated that he forgot that it was in his pocket and that it belonged to him. 1.1 Grams of suspected Marijuana was logged into evidence. Events recorded by body cam.
In result of the investigation White was charged with failure to illuminate head lamps, DUI 1st offense, and possession of marijuana and drug paraphernalia.
Blood kit was mailed on 01-12-2019 at West Main Street United States Post Office to Kentucky State Police Lab.

Narrative.NarrativeTxt: On 01-12-2019, at approximately 2052, I responded to a report of a physical domestic altercation at 109 Wedgewood Drive.

On 01-12-2019, at approximately 2052, I responded to a report of a physical domestic altercation at 109 Wedgewood Drive.
Upon arrival, I made contact with the complainant, Braydon Blanton, who stated that his brother, Cameron Blanton, had engaged in a physical altercation with their father, Mark Blanton. Braydon stated that an argument began when Braydon approached Cameron about a vehicle collision that Cameron had with Braydon's parked truck. Braydon stated that Cameron became aggressive and that Mark had stepped between the two of them to calm the situation. Braydon stated that Cameron then became aggressive towards Mark and then became physical with Mark.
Lt. McGuire and Ofc. Burgan arrived on scene and I made contact with Cameron and Mark. I observed the Cameron appeared to be upset and possibly under the influence of an unknown substance. I spoke with Mark who confirmed that the situation began with an argument between Braydon and Cameron. Mark stated that he had told Cameron not to operate the vehicle. Mark stated that he did step in between his sons and that Cameron then became physical with him. Mark stated that during the physical altercation, Cameron bit Mark on his right bicep, scratched the right side of his neck, and threw an unknown object that struck Mark in the face knocking his glasses off. I observed several red scratch marks on the right side of Mark's neck. I then observed a large red, black, and blue contusion on Mark's right bicep. Mark's glasses where also located on the floor in the kitchen where I observed other indicators of an altercation.
I then spoke with Cameron's friend, Travis Mitchell, who stated that he was present and witnessed the altercation. Travis confirmed Mark and Braydon's statement regarding the incident. Travis added that when Cameron engaged Mark his hands were both balled into fist and that Cameron was in a fighting and aggressive stance. Travis also stated that Cameron had taken Xanax earlier this date and that it took several of the individuals present to subdue Cameron from fighting.
When I attempted to speak with Cameron, Cameron's statements were varied and difficult to follow. Cameron did state that he felt he was the victim in the situation. Cameron was placed under arrest, cuffed, checked for fit, double locked, and transported to the Barren County Detention Center. Information was obtained for a report.
After the incident, I spoke with Ofc. Burgan who informed me that upon his arrival on scene he spoke with Braydon Blanton. Ofc. Burgan advised me that Braydon had stated that prior to the physical altercation between Mark and Cameron a handgun was present during the incident. Ofc. Burgan advised that Braydon had stated that the handgun present had originally belonged to their mother and had subsequently been passed down to Braydon and then Cameron. Ofc. Burgan advised that Braydon stated that during the argument between him and Cameron, Braydon was concerned about Cameron having access to the handgun and went to retrieve it to secure the weapon. Ofc. Burgan advised that Braydon stated that Cameron had then produced the handgun from his pocket and thrown the handgun at the wall. Ofc. Burgan advised that Braydon stated that the handgun was unloaded and that the firing pin had been removed prior to this incident. Ofc. Burgan advised that the family requested the handgun be seized and held for safe keeping. Ofc. Burgan advised that he secured the handgun and logged it into Evidence at the Glasgow Police Department.

Narrative.NarrativeTxt: On 01-12-2019, at approximately 2351, I responded to a report of damage to a vehicle in the parking lot of McDonald's, 101 Smith Road.

On 01-12-2019, at approximately 2351, I responded to a report of damage to a vehicle in the parking lot of McDonald's, 101 Smith Road.
Upon arrival, I made contact with the victim, Tonya Harper, and the two witnesses to the incident, Chasity Roberts and Angelia Pulliam. Tonya stated that she had received a call from her daughter, Chasity, at approximately 2330, that a Payton Sewell had thrown eggs at her black Nissan Altima. Tonya stated that Chasity had issues with Payton in the past due to both females previously dating the same guy. Tonya expressed concern that the eggs thrown at her vehicle could damage the paint and that she wanted the harassment towards Chasity to stop. I then spoke with Chasity who stated that her and her friend, Angelia, were sitting in the parking lot of Houchen's Southgate in the vehicle when the incident occurred. Chasity stated that her and Angelia both heard something strike the vehicle and looked to observe the surroundings. Chasity stated that her and Angelia both then observed a yellow 2005 Ford Mustang, driven by Payton Sewell, behind their vehicle. Chasity stated that she then observed the vehicle pull in front of her vehicle, observe that she was inside the vehicle, and then quickly drive away from the scene of the incident. Chasity then stated that she exited the vehicle and observed that the vehicle had been struck with eggs on the rear left side of the bumper. Chasity stated that she was very familiar with the yellow Mustang and knew that it was Payton's vehicle. Chasity stated that there were other vehicles in the parking lot however, no other persons were around prior to the incident. Angelia confirmed Chasity's statements of the incident.
While on scene, Angelia was able to make contact with Payton via text message. Tonya stated that she first wanted me to speak with Payton and advise her to stop the harassment and have no further contact. Angelia relaid the information via text message and stated that Payton refused to speak with law enforcement. Tonya then stated that she wanted to pursue charges for the damage. I observed the marks were the eggs had struck the rear left bumper. Chasity also provided a photo that she had taken of the eggs immediately after the incident had occurred. I obtained information for the report, advised Tonya to pursue charges with the CDW's Office, and cleared the scene without further incident.

Narrative.NarrativeTxt: On 01/16/2019 at 0626 hours, I was dispatched to 205 Newman Street in reference to a possible criminal mischief to a vehicle.

On 01/16/2019 at 0626 hours, I was dispatched to 205 Newman Street in reference to a possible criminal mischief to a vehicle.
Upon my arrival I made contact with H/F Amy Garcia, who advised me that between 01/15/2019 at 1800 hours and 01/16/2019 at 0620 hours, an unknown suspect(s) broke out her driver's side rear window with an unknown object on her white 2004 Chevy Tahoe (GA tag # 967-XBW), which was parked in her east side driveway in front of her residence. No other items were damaged or missing. The approximate amount of damage is $150.00.
Ms. Garcia further stated that she believes that a W/F Brittany Cedillo committed the criminal mischief to her vehicle, due to the fact that Ms. Cedillo accused Ms. Garcia for breaking out her windshield on her silver 2002 Honda van (KY tag # 967-XBW). Ms. Garcia also stated that Ms. Cedillo was having some type of relationship with her husband and was upset that they were not together.
I canvassed the area and did find any other damaged vehicles or further evidence.
At approximately 0700 hours, I made contact with W/F Cedillo at Happy Valley Inn in room 17, at which time she and her mother advised me that Ms. Cedillo had been present in the room at dusk and has not left the room at any time that evening until this time this morning.
I then spoke to a W/M James Burd, who also lives at the Happy Valley Inn in room 17, he advised me that he and Ms. Cedillo in the early evening hours on 01/15/2019 walked to his girlfriends house on the other side of town and stayed there for about an hour before returning to their room at the Happy Valley Inn. Mr. Burd would not disclose his girlfriends address, but did state it was about a 30 minute walk from their motel.
At this time, Ms. Cedillo spoke up and said, "Oh, yeah, we did go over his girlfriends house last night, but I did not break her window." I then asked Ms. Cedillo how did she know the victim only had one broken window when I said she had several broken windows? Ms. Cedillo was unable to answer my question. Ms. Cedillo still denied any involvement in reference to Ms. Garcia's broken vehicle window.
No further action taken at this time.

Narrative.NarrativeTxt: On 01/16/19, I observed a passenger car traveling East on Cumberland Parkway. The passenger vehicle was traveling 58 MPH in a posted 70 MPH zone. I followed the vehicle as it exited the parkway and onto Scottsville Road. The passenger vehicle(KY 875 VPT) was traveling South when it abruptly turned left onto Aberdeen Drive without signaling. I made contact with the operator, Nicholas Jackson, who advised he was following his GPS. While speaking with Jackson, I detected the odor of marijuana coming from the vehicle. I explained to Jackson what I detected and he admitted to having a small bag in the middle console. Jackson retrieved the bag of marijuana and gave it to me. I had Jackson exit the vehicle and he advised he had an ankle injury. Jackson and myself stepped to the rear of the vehicle. Jackson admitted to recently smoking marijuana. I asked when he last smoked marijuana and he stated "on my way here." I stood by while other units responded and I noticed that Jackson was standing on the heel of his right shoe. Jackson finished putting on his right shoe. I asked Jackson to remove his shoe and he advised he didn't want to because his ankle was hurt. I suspected Jackson might be impaired so I had Officer Greer administer ARIDE tests while I continued a search of the vehicle. According to Officer Greer, Jackson showed lack of convergence in his eyes. On the Modified Romberg test, Jackson estimated the passage of 30 seconds in 23 seconds. Jackson also exhibited eyes tremors during the Modified Romberg test. I had previously observed Jackson's eyes to be red. Due to Jackson claiming to be injuried and him visibly limping so balance test(s) were administered. Officer Moore conducted a pat down of Jackson and observed a handgun in Jackson's shoe. Officer Moore detained Jackson and I retrieved the handgun. The handgun was removed and unloaded. The handgun was a Ruger LCPZ .380. During a search of the vehicle, several small roaches were located. Dispatch found Jackson's operators license was suspended. Jackson was arrested and transported to TJ Samson Hospital for collection of blood. Once at TJ Samson Hospital, Jackson was read implied consent, declined when given an opportunity to contact an attorney, and gave a blood sample. Jackson declined when given an opportunity for an alternate test. Jackson was then transported to and lodged in the Barren County Jail. Officers observed at the hospital and the jail that Jackson was no longer walking with a limp.

Narrative.NarrativeTxt: On 01/14/2019 I was dispatched to a stolen phone report at the Traveler's Food Mart at 601 N. Race. On scene I spoke with the reporting party who advised she left her cell phone on the counter and unknown person took it.

On 01/14/2019 I was dispatched to the Traveler's Food Mart at 601 N.Race in regards to a stolen phone report. At the business I spoke with the victim, Benta Coffey. Ms. Coffey advised that she went into the business and placed her cell phone on the sole check out counter as she purchased her items. She then left the store.
As she began to drive out of the lot, she realized she had forgotten her phone and returned to the business. She went to the counter and the phone was gone.
Coffey advised that there were numerous people in line behind her as well as the two employees working the counter. There were no immediate suspects.
There are three video surveillance cameras on the check out counter. Store owner, Rameshkumar Patel, 09/18/1982, first advised that the cameras didn't record. When I pointed out the red "R" on the in store screen, Patel, advised that he couldn't get into the office because his wife had the key. Patel eventually advised that he will try to have a copy of the recorded cameras on 01/17/2019.
The second employee, Patricia Gibson, advised that she never saw the cell phone on the counter.
On 01/17/2019 I responded back to the Traveler's Food Mart and was advised by store personnel that there is no video available for this incident.
On 01/18/2019 I spoke with the complainant, Coffey, who advised that she had spoken with Apple and had the stolen phone locked and shut down. Coffey was advised that there was no video of the incident available and that the case would be closed based on the lack of investigative leads.
01/22/2019: Request to close this complaint based on the lack of a suspect or investigative leads.

Narrative.NarrativeTxt:
On 01/13/2019 I responded to 212 New Salem Road in reference to some stolen tools from a car port. Upon arrival I spoke with the victim, Darrell Gilley. Gilley advised he was missing multiple tools from a small building under his car port but not attached to the home. Gilley stated that he let his cat back in the house at around 3:00 AM that morning and advised that the door to the building was closed at this time. Gilley then stated that at 11:00 AM he returned outside and noticed that the building door was open and he had tools missing. Gilley advised that the door had been unlocked.
Gilley's mother, Mary Shockley, advised that she was leaving her son's home the night before when she observed a dark colored SUV suspiciously driving around the area. Shockley stated that the vehicle stopped at a nearby stop sign and would not pull out in front of her. Shockley advised she waited for a moment before pulling out and leaving but never saw the SUV pull away from the stop sign near her son's home.
Gilley advised the tools taken were valued at about $500.00. Gilley advised a tool box containing tire pressure gages, oil filters, spark plug gages, S.K wrench and socket sets (American and metric), another wrench and socket set (American and metric), screw drivers, drill bits, hex wrenches and a ratchet set was taken from the building. Also taken from the building was 2 butcher knives (one shaped to a curve), a jack stand and an air compressor.
Gilley could not provide serial numbers for any of the missing items.
Currently no leads and no suspects.

Narrative.NarrativeTxt: On 1/15/2019 I was dispatched to a injury accident on the Cumberland Parkway. Upon arrival I made contact with the operator, Zachary Driver. During my investigation Standard Field Sobriety Tests were conducted on Driver which resulted in him being placed under arrest for DUI as well as operating on a suspended license. Driver was transported to TJ Samson Community Hospital where he consented to a blood draw. Driver was then transported to the Barren County Detention Center where he was lodged.

On 1/15/2019 I was dispatched to the Cumberland Parkway (Westbound) between exits 14 and 11 in reference to a injury accident. Upon arrival I made contact with the operator of the above vehicle, Zachary Driver. Driver advised he was traveling on the parkway when two deer ran out in front of him in which he swerved to miss them and doing so he lost control of his vehicle and wrecked. Driver had blood on his hands and face in which EMS responded and a refusal was signed. I observed Driver's pupils to be small and did not react to light. Driver was asked if he had used any illegal drugs in which he advised he had taken a Tylenol 3 earlier at a friends house. Driver advised he did not have a prescription for Tylenol 3. I then performed Standard Field Sobriety Tests (SFST's) on Driver.
The first test was the Horizontal Gaze Nystagmus (HGN) test. Driver advised he had not suffered any traumatic event that had diagnosed him with Nystagmus. I observed equal pupil size, no resting Nystagmus in both eyes and equal tracking in both eyes. During the test, Nystagmus was observed during lack of smooth pursuit in both eyes. I also observed Nystagmus in both eyes at maximum deviation as well as onset prior to 45 degrees. No vertical Nystagmus was observed. The next test was the walk and turn. Driver stated he had a dislocated patella in his right knee. Driver advised he was able to continue with the test. During this test, Driver stepped off line during step 6 on the way down and performed a improper turn. No further clues were observed. The next test was the One Leg Stand Test. During this test Driver advised he understood the instructions and chose to lift his right foot off the ground. During the test Driver count "one-thousand thirteen" twice and then put his foot on the ground. Driver then resumed the test and no further clues were observed.
After the SFTS's were performed I placed Driver under arrest for DUI. Dispatch further advised his license was suspended and a suspension order had been issued. Driver was then transported to TJ Samson Community Hospital where he was read implied consent. Driver gave consent for a blood test and denied wanting a test conducted at his own expense. After leaving the hospital and while in route to the jail, Driver advised that earlier on 1/14/2019 around 12:00pm he had taken two Oxycodone pills that a friend had given him. Driver was then transported to the Barren County Detention Center where he was lodged.
The blood kit was placed in the mail by this officer.

On 01-17-2019, at approximately 1947, I responded to a report of shoplifting at Walmart, 2345 Happy Valley Road.
Upon arrival, I made contact with Asset Protection Officer, Sarah Moore, who stated that at approximately 1925, she observed an unknown white female, later identified as Chelsea Brianne Cooper, at the Walmart Self Checkout register 38. Sarah stated that she first observed Chelsea looking around suspiciously and then continued to observe. Sarah stated that as she continued to observe Chelsea, Sarah observed Chelsea take selected merchandise from her cart and conceal the merchandise in Walmart bags without scanning the items. Sarah stated that she observed Chelsea with a hand full of clothing items, scan (1) item, and then place all the clothing items in a Walmart bag. Sarah stated that she continued to observe Chelsea repeat this process of scanning (1) item and then placing other items with that Item in Walmart bags without scanning the addition items. Sarah stated that she then observed Chelsea pass all points of sale with the selected and concealed unscanned merchandise without providing payment.
I then spoke with Chelsea who was first read her Miranda Warning that she acknowledged and agreed to speak with me further. Chelsea stated and confirmed that she did take selected items, intentionally failed to scan those items, and concealed the unscanned items in Walmart bags. Chelsea then stated and confirmed that she then intentionally passed all points of sale with the concealed and unscanned merchandise without providing payment. Chelsea further stated that she was "down on her luck" and short of money. Chelsea also stated that she was a single parent with (1) child and a student.
I again spoke with Sarah who stated that the total amount concealed was $66.97 and that Chelsea had scanned and purchased $28.15. Sarah further provided a Walmart Asset Protection Report with photo of stolen merchandise of the incident and stated that she would provide surveillance video at a later date.
Chelsea was placed under arrest, cuffed, checked for fit, double locked, and transported to the Barren County Detention Center.

On 01-18-2019, at approximately 2046, I responded to a report of a physical domestic altercation at 502 Leslie Avenue. While responding, Dispatch further advised that the female in the altercation was bleeding and that EMS was responding.
Upon arrival, myself and Ofc. Burgan made contact and separated the parties involved, identified as Darren Carter and Jennifer Wright. Ofc. Burgan made contact with Jennifer while I spoke with Darren. EMS arrived on scene however, Jennifer refused treatment. Darren stated that Jennifer and himself had been in a relationship for the past two years and that the relationship was not going well. Darren stated that him and Jennifer have had issues in the past were law enforcement was notified however, no law enforcement action was taken. Darren stated that the current incident started due to him liking a photo on social media. Darren stated that when he arrived home from work, his son advised him that Jennifer had been drinking alcoholic beverages and had gotten on him when the son had arrived home earlier this date. Darren stated that he attempted to remove himself from any argument and was watching television in the living room. Darren stated that Jennifer came into the room and began arguing over the relationship issues. Darren stated that during the verbal argument, his son was standing at his bedroom door and that Jennifer then went towards him. Darren stated that he then intervened when Jennifer placed her hands on his son and he separated them. Darren stated that Jennifer then came at him, striking him with her hands on his chest. Darren stated that he attempted to push Jennifer away and that she fell backwards onto the floor. Darren stated that Jennifer then started throwing television remotes and other items at him. Darren stated that Jennifer then struck him in the back with a lamp. Darren stated that he did not have any visible injuries from the altercation. Darren then stated that he had a security camera in the room where the altercation occurred and provided me with that recording. I observed on the recording the incident as it was described by Darren.
I then made contact with Ofc. Burgan and Jennifer. Ofc. Burgan advised that Jennifer had stated and admitted to him that she was the aggressor in the incident. I also observed Jennifer state that she had gone after Darren and that she was the aggressor. I observed that Jennifer appeared very intoxicated and had an odor of an alcoholic beverage emitting from her breath and person. Ofc. Burgan advised that during his investigation Jennifer was not "bleeding" due to injury from the altercation but, that the she was "bleeding" due to the female reproductive cycle. Ofc. Burgan advised that Jennifer stated that she had back pain due to Darren pushing her away however, refused EMS.
Jennifer was then placed under arrest, cuffed, checked for fit, double locked, and transported to the Barren County Detention Center.

Narrative.NarrativeTxt: Unknown person took bicycle from front porch.

I was dispatched to 204 Mckenna St for a report of a stolen bicycle. I arrived and met with the RP Ben Shepherd. Shepherd told me that he had a charcoal Columbia beach cruiser with red rims and white walled tires. He had the bicycle on his front porch. He was in the process of selling the bicycle on Facebook Marketplace. Shepherd said that the bicycle was there on 01-18-19 around 2000hrs when he returned home. He found it missing 01-0=19-19 at approximately 1340hrs. He said that there was a prospective buyer for the bicycle who had the name of Maria on Messenger, she had asked to see the bicycle and Shepherd had given her his address 01-18-19 around 2300hrs. He told her to message him before she came over to see the bike. He had not heard from her after that. He also said that James Byrd had wanted to use the bike but he had told him he could not and he thought Byrd may have taken it. Shepherd asked his neighbors if they saw anyone and they all said they had not. I checked the area and was not able to locate the bicycle. Shepherd did not have any serial numbers
At approximately 1550hrs 01-19-19 I was contacted by Shepherd. he told me that he was informed by Melissa Houchens that the boyfriend of Brittany Shipley had told Houchens that he had taken the bicycle last night. Dispatch advised that units had checked out with Shipley and a male named Vincent McAllister during the night of 01-18-19. Shepherd told me that he had seen Shipley walking on Frazier St within five minutes of calling dispatch and she had told him she was going to the park to use wi-fi. I checked the area and was not able to locate Shipley or the bicycle. Shepherd said he was told she was staying on Bryan St but did not know where. I did not locate the bicycle on Bryan St.
I was on routine patrol on Happy Valley Rd near Garmon Ave at approximately 1715hrs when i observed a B/M riding a bicycle matching the description of the stolen one. I made contact with the male who was identified as Terrence Murphy 404-02-1462, OLKY M95479761, DOB 12-17-1973, Hillview Apts C8. He told me that he purchased the bicycle last night 01-18-19 from a W/M mid height driving a silver dually pick up with Todd Salvage and Scrap written on the side for $30. I made contact with the owner Shepherd. I asked him to identify the bicycle seat and writing on the side which he did. What he described matched the bike. I asked him to come to the scene and make a positive identification. He arrived and showed me the picture he had on Marketplace positively identifying it. I asked him if he wanted to prosecute the man and he said he did not want to. I returned the bike to Shepherd.

Narrative.NarrativeTxt: On 01/19/19 around 1950 hours, I conducted a traffic stop on a black 2008 Lincoln MKX after I observed it being operated with only one headlight illuminated. The traffic stop led to the arrest of the operator Cody Sexton.

On 01/19/19 around 1950 hours, I conducted a traffic stop on a black 2008 Lincoln MKX(KY 834 RXZ) after I observed it being operated with only one headlight illuminated. I made contact with the occupants of the vehicle and identified the operator as Cody Sexton. I asked that Officer Greer respond to my location to assist. Once Officer Greer arrived, I asked for consent to search the vehicle and Sexton gave verbal consent. Sexton exited the vehicle and Officer Greer started to check the contents of his pockets. Officer Greer advised he detected the odor of marijuana and that Sexton admitted to having a bag of marijuana in his pocket. Sexton had a Swisher Sweet package in his right front pants pocket and inside was a small bag of marijuana. I searched the vehicle and didn't locate any illegal drugs. Officer Greer then administered ARIDE test(s) on Sexton. On the lack of convergence test, Officer Greer advised Sexton's eyes showed lack of convergence. Officer Greer advised Sexton's eyes showed unequal tracking and lack of smooth pursuit. Officer Greer advised when he introduced light into Sexton's eyes they were bouncing(rebound dilation). On the Modified Romberg test, Officer Greer advised Sexton estimated the passage of 30 seconds in 27 seconds. Officer Greer advised that during the test, Sexton swayed as well as exhibited eye and body tremors. Sexton was arrested and transported to TJ Samson Hospital for collection of blood. Once at the hospital, Sexton was read the implied consent. Sexton then declined when given an opportunity to contact an attorney and gave a blood sample. I read Sexton his Miranda Warning and he advised he last smoked marijuana the night before. Sexton was then transported to and lodged in the Barren County Jail. The blood kit was sent to the KSP lab for analysis. I logged in the marijuana at the Glasgow Police Department. The bag of marijuana weighed approximately .3 grams.

Narrative.NarrativeTxt: I observed a speeder on Happy Valley Road while on routine patrol.

On 1-21-2019 while on routine patrol, I observed a vehicle traveling at a high rate of speed. Radar detected the subject traveling 58 in a 45 mph zone. Radar check OK. I then made a traffic stop on the vehicle. Once the stop was made, the subject told me he didn't have his operators licenses on his person. I ran the subject through LINK/NCIC and his drivers licenses was in force. I detected a strong presence of marijuana coming from the car the subject was driving. I also noticed the subject pupils were dilated. I ask the subject to step from the vehicle and perform an ARIDE sobriety test. The first test given was the Lack of Convergence test. On this test the subject showed clues of impairment by having lack of smooth pursuit and equal tracking in both eyes. The subject also swayed as the test was administered. The subject had lack of convergence in his eyes. The next test given was the Modified Rhomberg balance test. On this test the subject showed clues of impairment by having eye and body tremors. The subject also swayed as the test was administered. The subject used 25 seconds on the 30 seconds allotted for the test. The subject was placed in custody and he was placed in my cruiser. I ask him before he was put my cruiser if I could search his car and the subject consented to the search. During the search, I located a plastic bag with a small amount of marijuana inside. It was located in the trunk of the subject car. I also located a lot of loose marijuana inside the seat areas of the subject car. The subject had a vape pen on his person with THC inside the vape according to the subject. I then transported the subject to T. J. Samson Hospital for a blood draw. Once at the hospital the subject was read the implied consent warning. The subject refused to speak to a attorney at this time. The subject consented to a test of his blood. Once the test was completed, the subject refused a test of his blood at his expense. The subject was then transported to the Barren County Detention Center where he was lodged.

Narrative.NarrativeTxt: Investigating a person acting erratically in the store and parking lot

On 01-21-19 at 1003hrs I responded to the Dollar Tree for a report of a female acting erratically. I arrived and was directed to a B/F wearing a camouflaged jacket and gray pants. I could see she was uncontrollably jerking as she walked around the store. I made contact with her and asked for an ID. She said it was in her truck in the parking lot. OFC Moore was running the tag which came back to Carter. She gave me her ID which identified her as Claresa Carter. She said that she did not feel as if she was acting anyway out of the ordinary. Carter was having uncontrollable muscle movements of the head and upper body, she had a slight slur when she spoke, her right side of her face was pulled back when she spoke and she was chewing as she spoke. All are signs that my experience has shown are consistent with drug use OFC Rees arrived and asked her if we could search the vehicle. Carter gave permission to search. I asked her if she had taken anything illegal, she said she only took prescribed medicines. She said she took medicine for heart issues and was diabetic. Carter said that she had recently been discharged from the hospital where she was diagnosed with the medical conditions, on 01-16-19. That day was when she was given the medications that she was taking for the medical conditions. OFC Rees and Moore located three bottles with Claresa Carter written on them. One was Alprazolam which was filled with 30 pills on 01-08-19 and was empty. The second was Hydrocodone filled 07-17 with one pill inside ,and the third was Phertermine which Carter said was for weight loss. I asked her if she had taken the pills today, she said that she had taken her medications for diabetes and her heart pill. I asked if she had eaten which she said she had. This made me think there may also be some medical issues along with suspected illegal drug use, or misuse/abuse of her prescribed medications. I made contact with her husband Jason and asked him if this was usual behavior for her. He said it was not. Carter stated that she had also taken a pain pill indicating she had taken the Hydrocodone possibly. I had EMS come to the scene and check her out. They advised that she did not want to be transported.OFC Rees and Moore located a .22cal handgun Ruger in her purse, she does not have a CCDW. Carter was placed under arrest and taken to TJ Samson ER to be medically cleared. Carter was cleared and taken to the Barren County Detention Center. She continued to have twitchy movements throughout the encounter.

On 01-23-2019 I received a call from probation and parole officer Jason Alexander. Alexander advised he had received a tip that one of his clients Bambi Nicole Gentry, was selling meth from a house located at 100 Blackwood. Alexander then requested I assist him in searching the residence. At approximately 1051 hours I arrived on scene with Alexander and another officer from probation and parole. We made contact with the home owner, identified as Chris Gentry, at the front of the residence. Officers requested and was granted a written consent to search the residence. While searching the residence officers located a wooden box in an end table drawer. The wooden box contained tooter straws, a meth pipe, a small baggie containing a white powdery substance believed to be Meth, and a set of digital scales. Mr Gentry advised officers those items belonged to him.
Ms. Gentry was also arrested on probation violation charges by Alexander. a Second male inside the residence was also arrest on a Marion County Warrant for failure to appear. The wooden box with Meth and paraphernalia was seized and later logged into evidence at the Glasgow Police Dept.
Both Mr and Ms Gentry were transported and lodged in the Barren County Jail without incident. Both subjects were cuffed in the rear.
